WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.550
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today, we're&nbsp;
going to look at our new framework for maxwells,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:24.150
where we extend our labeling set from natural&nbsp;
numbers to integers. This extends our view&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.150 --> 00:00:30.930
so that we're essentially covering the&nbsp;
entire plane now with possible pixels. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:37.740
it's a much broader framework, and we want to&nbsp;
review some of the hopefully familiar aspects of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.740 --> 00:00:44.010
the previous maxwell theory in this new setting.&nbsp;
It will be a chance to first of all review some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.010 --> 00:00:49.740
important things and also get you used to thinking&nbsp;
more two-dimensionally about linear algebra.

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:57.030
The basic objects are these things called maxwells&nbsp;
from integers, where we're considering multisets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.030 --> 00:01:02.430
of pixels where the pixels themselves can have&nbsp;
entries that are integers, including both negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:09.750
and natural numbers. So here, for example, is a&nbsp;
maxwell. It's an M-set of pixels, and the various&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:16.200
pixels can be represented by the positions on this&nbsp;
screen, which we might call the integer screen.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:22.500
It's typically in green here, with these two&nbsp;
prominent vertical and horizontal bars that align&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:29.700
things and tell you where the indices start. So,&nbsp;
this is the central element whose indices are (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.700 --> 00:01:36.720
0), and then we go down here—the first entry&nbsp;
increases, so (0, 0), (1, 0), (2, 0), and so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:44.430
on. When we go to the right, we go (0, 0),&nbsp;
(0, 1), (0, 2), (0, 3), and so forth. That,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.430 --> 00:01:52.860
of course, then extends to the negative values as&nbsp;
well. So, for example, this "3" here is referring&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:59.670
to the fact that we have 3 pixels of this&nbsp;
type: (-2, -1). So that will be (-2, -1).

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:06.870
The other important ingredient is our&nbsp;
multiplication of pixels, which is the fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:16.140
building block for the algebra of maxwells. This&nbsp;
is the crucial multiplication: KL × MN = KN,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:24.450
provided that L = M, and otherwise blank or empty.&nbsp;
This multiplication now is a multiplication of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:31.050
pixels from integers, so now the entries here&nbsp;
can be integers, not just natural numbers.

00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:37.890
Alright, so let me remind you of some notations—a&nbsp;
basic notation that helps us understand maxwells.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:44.400
The idea of a one-maxwell is a simple kind&nbsp;
of maxwell that only has one element in it:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:51.660
a single pixel, namely (i, j). Now,&nbsp;
of course, the i and j indices can be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:59.070
any integers. A special kind is the diagonal&nbsp;
one-maxwell, where they are in the form e_ii,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:06.720
so the two elements are the same. These occur&nbsp;
on the diagonal, and they have the idempotent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:14.460
property: e_ii² = e_ii. If you multiply one&nbsp;
of these diagonal ones with another one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:19.200
you either get the one that you started&nbsp;
with, if they're both the same—that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:27.540
basically this rule here—or, if they're not&nbsp;
the same, you get the zero-maxwell. So this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.540 --> 00:03:32.550
zero here represents the zero-maxwell,&nbsp;
the empty maxwell—just the empty set.

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:41.400
Here's our picture of our screen with our&nbsp;
two canonical vertical and horizontal lines.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:48.750
There's the (0, 0) spot, so this now is the&nbsp;
place or the home for (0, 0). Here's e_11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.750 --> 00:04:00.180
e_22, e_-1,-1, e_-2,-2, etc. So actually, if&nbsp;
we drew a representation for, say, e_-1,-1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:06.540
we would end up with a single "1" there and&nbsp;
zeros everywhere else. These are kind of units&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:16.920
in the world of maxwells, and prominently,&nbsp;
we can go either in this direction or we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:20.440
carry on in this direction here as well.&nbsp;
So, it is a two-sided aspect of things.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:34.060
Now, suppose that J is a set from integers—it's&nbsp;
a set of integers. Then e_J is the sum of little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:42.250
j belonging to capital J of these e_j,j's.&nbsp;
And I need to remind you that when I say set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.250 --> 00:04:45.880
I always mean something that&nbsp;
you can actually write down,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:52.570
so it's an explicit set in our standard&nbsp;
notation. So, it's by definition finite,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:59.230
okay? We don't even consider infinite things&nbsp;
because you can't write them down, okay? So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:59.230 --> 00:05:03.820
this kind of J we will call an identity&nbsp;
maxwell or maybe a partial identity maxwell.

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:15.790
For example, if J is the set {-2, 0, 1}, then&nbsp;
it can be represented as e_J here. So here's our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.790 --> 00:05:21.730
basic two lines—a bit of a crowded diagram, but&nbsp;
you see a "1" there, that "1" represents that zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.730 --> 00:05:29.290
there, the -2 there, another one there, and this&nbsp;
one represents there. So, this thing here is e_11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.290 --> 00:05:40.180
this is e_00, and this is e_-2,-2. So in&nbsp;
terms of pixels, here is the M-set e_J.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:47.560
Let's just talk a little bit about rows and&nbsp;
columns. So, we have this J—we can also talk&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:52.780
about the rows of J and the columns of J, and that&nbsp;
will be important for us. The rows of J are just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.780 --> 00:06:02.170
the rows that go through the various entries of&nbsp;
J, while the columns are these ones here—again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:09.670
they go through the various diagonal entries&nbsp;
that are represented by J. So, here we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:16.300
the rows of this particular J, and here are the&nbsp;
columns of this particular J, three of each side.

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:24.580
Now, if M is any maxwell, then the product&nbsp;
e_J M is the restriction of M to the rows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:32.520
of J. The effect of multiplying by e_J—this is&nbsp;
just the same kind of story that happens in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:37.440
case we started talking about when we&nbsp;
were just restricting to indices 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:43.080
2, 3, and so on. The algebra is&nbsp;
completely the same. The e_J M&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.080 --> 00:06:52.260
is the restriction of M to the rows of&nbsp;
J, while the other way around, M × e_J,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:57.840
is the restriction to the columns of J—mainly&nbsp;
a restriction here. In other words, basically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:04.290
forget about all the entries of M that are outside&nbsp;
the columns or, in this case, outside the rows.

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:11.070
Then, if we combine those two ideas, we have a&nbsp;
maxwell M, and we multiply on the left by e_J&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.070 --> 00:07:18.330
and on the right also by e_J, then we get the&nbsp;
cumulative effect of restricting to the rows of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.330 --> 00:07:27.960
J and to the columns of J. So, for example, if J&nbsp;
is the same as before: {-2, 0, 1}, then e_J looks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:35.850
like this, and here's e_J as well. And suppose we&nbsp;
take some arbitrary maxwell M—we multiply it by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:41.820
e_J on the left and e_J on the right. What do&nbsp;
we get? Well, it's an excellent exercise to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:48.390
convince yourself that this is what you get—that&nbsp;
we end up just looking at the rows and the columns&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:59.880
associated with J. So, the rows of J would be the&nbsp;
-2 row, the 0 row, and the 1 row. Column J would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:09.030
be the -2 column, the 0 column, and the 1 column.&nbsp;
If we ignore everything that is not in both the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.030 --> 00:08:14.790
rows and columns that I've just mentioned, then we&nbsp;
get this thing here. So, this is the restriction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:31.080
of this to the row -2, 0, and 1, and to the column&nbsp;
-2 down there, 0 over there, and 1 over there. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:39.390
everything outside gets killed, and everything&nbsp;
that's in, say, one row but not a column ends&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.390 --> 00:08:47.730
up being killed. So, the only entries that are&nbsp;
left are the ones in the rows and columns of J.

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:55.410
This very much parallels what we've done in&nbsp;
previous videos when we talked about maxwell&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.410 --> 00:09:01.590
algebra, so you might want to go back to some&nbsp;
of those to remind yourself. If we have a set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:09.750
J, a set of integers, then we can consider J × J,&nbsp;
and by that, we mean the set of lists of the form&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:18.180
(j_1, j_2), where j_1 and j_2 belong to J. So,&nbsp;
this is a set of pixels from integers because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:25.170
this is just a pixel from integers, and a set&nbsp;
of pixels from integers we will call a frame.

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:37.950
So, then max J × J is the type of a maxwell&nbsp;
M whose support is in J × J. With our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.950 --> 00:09:48.720
example of J = {-2, 0, 1}, here are our standard&nbsp;
lines—there's the (0, 0) position—then the J × J&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:57.030
frame looks like what? Well, first of all, here's&nbsp;
an e_-2,-2, e_00, and e_11. So here are sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.030 --> 00:10:07.380
the basic entries, the diagonal entries that&nbsp;
define e_J. Then, the positions that correspond to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:16.470
columns and rows are just these ones here: 1, 2,&nbsp;
3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9. So these are the pixels whose&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.470 --> 00:10:28.830
rows are either 1, 0, or -2, and whose columns are&nbsp;
either 1, 0, or -2, and there are nine of them.

00:10:28.830 --> 00:10:39.570
So, when we talk about max J × J, we're talking&nbsp;
about all the maxwells whose support is this or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:46.820
is contained in this particular frame—the&nbsp;
frame consisting of these nine positions in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.820 --> 00:10:56.960
our integer screen. So, this is going to be a&nbsp;
maxwell subalgebra of max int. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:03.740
if you take the product or the sum of any two&nbsp;
such things, you're going to stay inside this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:14.480
closed algebra. So, this is a very nice, flexible&nbsp;
way of finding essentially what we might call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:21.890
matrix algebra, okay, traditionally. But we&nbsp;
can find them now anywhere or everywhere on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:21.890 --> 00:11:29.360
our screen in this kind of symmetrical&nbsp;
way. You pick a subset J of integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.360 --> 00:11:36.470
and then that's basically picking a bunch of&nbsp;
diagonal elements along the diagonal, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:44.390
associated with that, you have this something like&nbsp;
a square thing—but it's not graphically a square,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.390 --> 00:11:52.370
but it's arithmetically a square—of positions&nbsp;
that support this maxwell subalgebra.

00:11:55.070 --> 00:12:02.660
Alright, so this is by way of review but also an&nbsp;
extension of the ideas that we had before in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:09.470
natural number case. We're now extending this&nbsp;
to cover the entire plane—that's the crucial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:09.470 --> 00:12:16.430
difference. We're now allowing arbitrary&nbsp;
integers to be indices for our pixels.

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:22.580
Now, we are going to see that this&nbsp;
maxwell algebra, extended to integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:26.390
has a lot of beautiful properties.&nbsp;
It will be very useful for us when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:32.150
we want to talk about extension fields&nbsp;
or more general sorts of field theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:37.760
but we'll also see that it has a lot of&nbsp;
connections with calculus. Having this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:43.760
two-sided aspect of things will play a very big&nbsp;
role when we connect things with calculus ideas.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:52.820
A very useful tool in this understanding is the&nbsp;
idea of shifting along the diagonal. It turns out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:58.040
that the entire maxwell framework that we've&nbsp;
been talking about is kind of invariant under&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:06.050
shifting diagonally along the diagonal line, and&nbsp;
we can make that more precise by introducing a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:06.050 --> 00:13:14.030
formal shift operation. So, for k an integer,&nbsp;
let's define S_k. This is going to be a shift&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:21.080
on pixels from integers, defined in the following&nbsp;
way. So here, m and n are a pixel from integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:30.680
and S_k is our shift. By definition,&nbsp;
this is going to be (m + k, n + k). So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:38.090
what we're doing is we're adding k to both&nbsp;
values at the same time—that's effectively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:44.810
shifting it diagonally in this direction if k is&nbsp;
positive and in this direction if k is negative.

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:52.820
Okay, so now I'm going to leave you with a couple&nbsp;
of exercises. The first one is to show that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.820 --> 00:14:02.150
respects multiplication. This is a crucial one:&nbsp;
that if you have two pixels p and q, and you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:02.150 --> 00:14:08.870
interested in multiplying them, then the shift&nbsp;
of their product is the same as the product of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.870 --> 00:14:14.600
their shifts. So, if you shift p and you shift q&nbsp;
and then you multiply, that's the same as first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:23.300
multiplying p and q and then shifting. Also,&nbsp;
show that there's a kind of composite property,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:29.690
which is almost obvious: that if you shift by&nbsp;
k and then you shift by l, it's the same as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.690 --> 00:14:39.620
shifting by l + k. So, the shifts themselves&nbsp;
have a kind of pleasant algebraic aspect.

00:14:41.570 --> 00:14:46.730
Generally speaking, once we've defined something&nbsp;
for pixels, we want to extend that to maxwells,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:51.290
which are just M-sets of pixels.&nbsp;
So, we know how to shift pixels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:56.570
so it follows that we should be able to&nbsp;
shift maxwells just by doing the M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.570 --> 00:15:03.590
version of the shifting—namely, shift&nbsp;
all the pixels in a given maxwell. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:03.590 --> 00:15:10.340
we'll do that. We'll define the shift S_k—k&nbsp;
is still an integer—from pixels to maxwells,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:16.520
and it's just the M-set extension.&nbsp;
Let me illustrate it with an example.

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:26.030
So, here is a maxwell—it has a few pixels,&nbsp;
four of them—and let's say that k equals 2. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.030 --> 00:15:34.370
the S_k of M—we're going to apply S_k to each&nbsp;
one of these pixels, so it's a new multiset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:34.370 --> 00:15:41.930
with S_k of this, and S_k of this, S_k of&nbsp;
this, and S_k of this. Each one of these,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.930 --> 00:15:45.950
individually, we're just shifting&nbsp;
by 2. So, if we shift this by 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:53.120
we get (0, 5); also (0, 5); here we get&nbsp;
(3, 2); and here, I guess we get (-1, 1).

00:15:53.120 --> 00:16:04.220
Diagrammatically, this maxwell here is,&nbsp;
let's see, there's a (-2, 3), (-2, 3),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:15.830
so there's two of them; there's a (1, 0)—that's&nbsp;
that one there; there's a (-3, -1)—(-3, -1);&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:24.440
so this is the representation of this maxwell. And&nbsp;
when we shift it by 2, it means we're shifting in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:29.570
this direction here diagonally. So, everything&nbsp;
goes down in that direction—two down this way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.570 --> 00:16:36.650
two across this way. So, the one that's appearing&nbsp;
here goes there, the two that were here go there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:36.650 --> 00:16:44.720
the one that was here goes there. So, the whole&nbsp;
thing has just moved down diagonally by two.

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:51.170
Now let's identify some important&nbsp;
features of this shifting of maxwells.

00:16:51.170 --> 00:16:59.150
Say, shift invariants for maxwells, and&nbsp;
let's summarize things in the theorem. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:07.520
if k is an integer, and M and N are maxwells&nbsp;
from integers, then the shift S_k(M) + the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:18.920
shift S_k(N) equals the shift S_k(M + N), so&nbsp;
it respects addition. If you add two maxwells&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:28.240
and then shift, it's the same as first shifting&nbsp;
and then adding. That's almost obvious. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.240 --> 00:17:38.290
a little bit more subtle: that S_k(M) × S_k(N)&nbsp;
is S_k(MN). If you multiply M and N and shift,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:38.290 --> 00:17:45.910
it's the same thing as first shifting M and&nbsp;
shifting N and then multiplying them. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:50.770
to summarize: this shifting does not&nbsp;
really affect the algebra of maxwells.

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:59.290
This is an aspect of matrix multiplication—it's&nbsp;
not very complicated, but it's something that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:03.850
not that visible in standard linear algebra&nbsp;
because we're usually working there in a fixed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:09.610
framework. We're working with 3x3 matrices&nbsp;
or 4x5 matrices or something like that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.610 --> 00:18:14.740
so we have a fixed kind of framework. It doesn't&nbsp;
really make sense to shift everything down because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:19.840
then we would sort of move out of the domain in&nbsp;
which we're working. But now, we have this more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:23.980
flexible, bigger point of view. We're working&nbsp;
in the entire plane—we're not restricted by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:30.880
any kind of boundaries, and so the shifting is&nbsp;
a more natural thing that's more visible to us.

00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:38.260
Here's a little exercise: you can verify the&nbsp;
theorem for these two particular maxwells. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.260 --> 00:18:46.960
they're cute little maxwells, only 2x2. Here's&nbsp;
2, 1, 3, 4—that maxwell there—and the N is 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:53.620
2, 1, 3. You can try, say, for different&nbsp;
values of k and just verify that it works.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.620 --> 00:19:00.820
And even better, you can sort of write&nbsp;
out proofs of why these formulas hold.

00:19:00.820 --> 00:19:09.340
So, we're now in quite a nice position.&nbsp;
We've extended our labeling or our index&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.340 --> 00:19:15.940
sets so that now we can consider indices that take&nbsp;
on arbitrary integer values. It's a big expansion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:23.290
but we also want to expand in another important&nbsp;
way, okay, which is different but still utilizes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:28.150
this bigger picture of having integers at&nbsp;
our disposal now, not just natural numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.150 --> 00:19:39.250
And that is that we want to extend things so that&nbsp;
the actual entries of our maxwells are themselves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:39.250 --> 00:19:46.090
possibly negative. We don't always want to be&nbsp;
just considering natural number entries—we want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.090 --> 00:19:52.420
to have a -2 possibly in a matrix. Of course,&nbsp;
we want to do that, so we have to set that up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.420 --> 00:19:59.470
though, because this "2" here represents a&nbsp;
multiplicity of a certain number of pixels. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:05.170
in order to make sense of what that might mean&nbsp;
if that was -2 instead, we have to get our heads&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:05.170 --> 00:20:11.950
around what it means to talk about -2 pixels or,&nbsp;
in fact, what it means to talk about -2 anything.

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:20.470
So, we've talked about -2—we've introduced&nbsp;
-2 as this abstract integer object, something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.470 --> 00:20:29.800
that we write down. But how do we multiply&nbsp;
that -2 by something else? In particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:36.670
how do we multiply -2 by a pixel? To understand&nbsp;
that, we are going to have to go back to our&nbsp;&nbsp;

